        <briefdescription>
<para>returns the power product of <computeroutput>pw</computeroutput> and <computeroutput>qw</computeroutput>. </para>        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>Let <formula id="101">$ {p}^{(w)} = (p,w_p), p\in\mathbb{R}^2, w_p\in\mathbb{R}$</formula> and <formula id="102">$ {q}^{(w)}=(q,w_q), q\in\mathbb{R}^2, w_q\in\mathbb{R}$</formula> be two weighted points.</para><para>The <emphasis>power product</emphasis>, also called <emphasis>power distance</emphasis> between <formula id="103">$ {p}^{(w)}$</formula> and <formula id="104">$ {q}^{(w)}$</formula> is defined as <formula id="105">\[ \Pi({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)}) = {\|{p-q}\|^2-w_p-w_q} \]</formula> where <formula id="106">$ \|{p-q}\|$</formula> is the Euclidean distance between <formula id="107">$ p$</formula> and <formula id="108">$ q$</formula>.</para><para>The weighted points <formula id="103">$ {p}^{(w)}$</formula> and <formula id="104">$ {q}^{(w)}$</formula> are said to be <emphasis>orthogonal</emphasis> iff <formula id="109">$ \Pi{({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)})} = 0$</formula>.</para><para>Three weighted points have, in 2D, a unique common orthogonal weighted point called the <emphasis>power circle</emphasis>. The <emphasis>power segment</emphasis> will denote the weighted point orthogonal to two weighted points on the line defined by these two points. </para>        </detaileddescription>
